description: See sym- and Ancient Greek φρήν (phrḗn, “mind”).

adjectives.description: symphronistic (comparative more symphronistic, superlative most symphronistic)

entries.meaning: (uncommon) Identical in terms of intellect or signification.
examples: 1885,  Johann Wolfgang von Goethe,  chapter II, in  Wilhelm Meister’s Travels‎[1], Boston: George Barrie, page 85:“Just as you see,” rejoined the old man; “for you will observe that in the plinths and friezes are represented not so much synchronistic as symphronistic* actions and events, whilst among all nations there occur traditions of similar and equal import.
